Runnable r = () -> System.out.println("Hello!");
With parameters:

(int a, int b) -> System.out.println(a + b);

Single statement body (no braces needed):
str -> str.length()

What is a Functional Interface?
A Functional Interface is an interface that contains exactly one abstract method.
It can have multiple default or static methods, but only one abstract method.

It is used as the target type for lambda expressions, method references, or constructor references.
A lambda expression in Java can only be used:
where the target type is a functional interface â€” an interface with exactly one abstract method.